\begin_layout Standard
As seen, the two measurements differ significantly; the current measured
 by the CAEN is considerably higher than the current measured by the probe
 station, and the current measured in the probe station has an extra kink
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim80-90\UNIT V$
\end_inset

.
 To account for these differences let's consider the following expressions
 for the current in each case
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\LBRACE{\begin{aligned} & I_{\text{CAEN}}\approx4I_{\text{pad}}+I_{\text{guard ring}}\\
 & I_{\text{probe station}}\approx I_{\text{pad}}+I_{\text{guard ring}}
\end{aligned}
}
\]

\end_inset

 after the connections described for each case.
 If we focus in the region where the gain layer depletes the change in the
 total current (i.e.
 the measured current) should be dominated by the variations in 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\text{pad}}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{guard ring}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\ll\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{pad}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 Following this idea we should observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{CAEN}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\approx4\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{probe station}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 The depletion of the gain layer is happening between 
\begin_inset Formula $-35\UNIT V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-40\UNIT V$
\end_inset

 approximately.
 In the measurement using the probe station the increase between 
\begin_inset Formula $-35\UNIT V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-40\UNIT V$
\end_inset

 is of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{probe station}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\approx135\NANO A-94.3\NANO A=40.7\NANO A\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

 For the measurement with the CAEN the current increase in the same voltage
 range is about 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\EVALUATEDAT{\frac{\DIFERENTIAL I_{\text{CAEN}}}{\DIFERENTIAL V}}{\text{Gain layer depletes}}{}\approx350\NANO A-190\NANO A=160\NANO A\text{.}
\]

\end_inset

The ratio of these two currents is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{160\NANO A}{40.7\NANO A}=3.9
\]

\end_inset

which seem to indicate that the previous reasoning is correct.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With respect to the difference at 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx-90\UNIT V$
\end_inset

, the second kink in the measurement with the probe station, not present
 on the measurement with the CAEN, may be due to border effects in the pads
 left floating.
 
\end_layout

